{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:57:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:57:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20834"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20834"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13709"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97043"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13709"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79659"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11660"},{"type":"tags","id":"11776"},{"type":"tags","id":"12659"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33009"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33010"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97043"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFoetal alcohol syndrome results from maternal alcohol consumption during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a characteristic feature of foetal alcohol syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accelerated psychomotor development","Macrocephaly","Elongated palpebral fissures","Mandibular hypoplasia","Prenatal growth restriction"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFoetal alcohol syndrome is a condition that results from maternal alcohol consumption during pregnancy. \u003Cstrong\u003EPrenatal growth restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature of this syndrome, along with postnatal growth restriction, specific facial anomalies, and psychomotor disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrocephaly\u003C/strong\u003E - Foetal alcohol syndrome is associated with microcephaly (small head circumference), not macrocephaly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElongated palpebral fissures\u003C/strong\u003E - Short palpebral fissures (eye openings) are characteristic of foetal alcohol syndrome, not elongated ones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMandibular hypoplasia\u003C/strong\u003E - Maxillary hypoplasia (underdevelopment of the middle portion of the face) is characteristic, not mandibular hypoplasia\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccelerated psychomotor development\u003C/strong\u003E - Foetal alcohol syndrome causes psychomotor disturbances and developmental delays, not acceleration\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that alcohol is a teratogen that can cause these effects even when consumed in modest amounts during pregnancy. The combination of growth restriction, facial anomalies, and psychomotor disturbances constitutes the diagnostic criteria for foetal alcohol syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Foetal alcohol syndrome is characterised by prenatal and postnatal growth restriction, facial anomalies, and psychomotor disturbances.","Even modest alcohol consumption during pregnancy can cause teratogenic effects on the developing foetus.","Key facial features of foetal alcohol syndrome include microcephaly, short palpebral fissures, and maxillary hypoplasia."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 10; page 455."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79659"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20834"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79659"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:46:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:46:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13709"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97043"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11660"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Concepts in congenital abnormalities","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":9,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11776"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Causes of anomalies","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-11T18:16:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T18:16:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12659"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Environmental (including infections)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-04-01T08:34:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T08:34:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr